{"key":"processedPost-15604707","value":{"id":15604707,"first":15599953,"last":15635909,"when":1325524188,"utime":"01/02/12 07:09 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>jenia1 said:</strong><br />my agar procedures are exactly like in RR's vid. opening the sleeve infront of the hood no more than 4\"&nbsp; and keeping it for later, sterilizing for 30m than pouring it without blocking the flow of the sterile air from the hood</blockquote><br />'Sterilizing' for 30 minutes might be the problem.&nbsp; You need to let all the air escape from your pressure cooker by leaving the steam vent off/open for at least ten minutes before sealing it up to build pressure.&nbsp; Once pressure is reached, I keep it at 15 psi for 40 minutes, not 30.<br />A common mistake is not venting steam enough before sealing the unit.&nbsp; 15 pounds of air pressure is not the same as 15 pounds of steam pressure, but both read the same on the gauge.&nbsp; If you don't get all the air out, you have air pressure, not steam.<br />RR","title":"Re: 1st time using flow hood, still no luck=/"}}